BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:This event is part of Love Data Week at Stanford\, an annual fe
 stival highlighting topics\, opportunities and services relevant to data in
  research. \n\nJoin us in mapping a high-priority global health project\, h
 elping organizations like Doctors without Borders and the Red Cross deliver
  vital aid to at-risk communities around the world. In just 20 minutes\, yo
 u'll join a movement of over 100K volunteers across the world using Humanit
 arian OpenStreetMap (HOTOSM). \n\nIn our Winter Mapathon\, we’ll be using s
 atellite imagery and simple online GIS tools to trace building outlines\, c
 reating detailed digital maps of unmapped areas. Last spring\, we mapped 20
 84 buildings in Malawi and hope to break that record! This Winter\, we’ll b
 e mapping a high-priority global health project that helps organizations li
 ke Doctors Without Borders and the Red Cross deliver vital\, life-saving ai
 d. Through Missing Maps\, these efforts are sustained in collaboration with
  local communities\, ensuring long-term resilience in the regions we map.\n
 \nREGISTER HERE: https://luma.com/iekdb0rh\n\nOpen to all Stanford affiliat
 es in person or over Zoom & dinner will be provided!Non-Stanford affiliates
  may join us over Zoom! \nZoom: https://stanford.zoom.us/j/91622371366?pwd=
 ytaMaENiIgaR6rnR7HScVgPwA2NpRr.1&from=addon\n\nWhat is a Mapathon? Accurate
  maps are essential for humanitarian responses and global health—yet many c
 ommunities remain unmapped. Missing Maps is a humanitarian initiative start
 ed in 2014 to address this critical gap by mapping crucial infrastructure i
 n underrepresented areas\, often through collaborative “Mapathon” events. T
 he maps created help emergency responders reach communities during natural 
 disasters\, enable healthcare workers to organize vaccination campaigns\, a
 nd support NGOs in developing resilient infrastructure. \n\nSo\, join us fo
 r an evening of impact on Monday February 9th from 6-8 pm in Branner Earth 
 Sciences Library. No prior experience is necessary—mapping is easy to learn
  in just 20 minutes—so come ready to have fun while contributing to a globa
 l humanitarian effort. We can’t wait to see you there!\n\nWe will be taking
  photos at this event for publicity purposes. Your presence at this event c
 onstitutes consent to be photographed unless you express otherwise.
DTEND:20260210T040000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083906Z
DTSTART:20260210T020000Z
GEO:37.426402;-122.172635
LOCATION:Mitchell Earth Sciences\, Branner Earth Sciences Library & Map Col
 lections
SEQUENCE:0
