BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Why do we sometimes procrastinate even on the things we care de
 eply about? And how can we create motivation that actually lasts—beyond dea
 dlines\, or external pressure? In this interactive workshop\, we’ll explore
  the psychological science behind motivation and procrastination\, with a s
 pecial focus on avoidance loops due to fear of failure\, perfectionism\, an
 d stress. Through a liberatory and compassionate lens\, we’ll uncover what 
 really drives our behavior—and how to rewire our routines in ways that feel
  sustainable and self-honoring. Participants will leave with a personalized
  motivation profile and tools to transform avoidance into aligned action.\n
 \nLearning Objectives:\n\nDefine key psychological terms including: intrins
 ic motivation\, procrastination\, and activation energy.Identify internal a
 nd external factors that influence motivation and avoidance.Understand the 
 connection between perfectionism\, fear of failure\, and procrastination.Ap
 ply research-backed techniques to build habits rooted in values\, not press
 ure.Create a sustainable motivation plan based on personal rhythms and goal
 s.Experience Level: Intermediate \n\nRegister Here\n\nFacilitated by:  Dr. 
 Meag-gan O'Reilly\, CEO & CO-Founder of Inherent Value Psychology INC\n\nAb
 out Quick Bytes:\n\nGet valuable professional development wisdom that you c
 an apply right away! Quick Bytes sessions cover a variety of topics and inc
 lude lunch. Relevant to graduate students at any stage in any degree progra
 m.\n\nSee the full Quick Bytes schedule
DTEND:20260210T211500Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083906Z
DTSTART:20260210T200000Z
LOCATION:Tresidder Oak West\, Oak West Lounge
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Quick Bytes: The Science of Motivation & Procrastination: How to Ha
 ck Your Habits for Sustainable Success
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51438040756024
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/quick-bytes-the-science-of-motivation
 -procrastination-how-to-hack-your-habits-for-sustainable-success
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:Join the Tech Impact and Policy Center on February 10th from 12
 PM–1PM Pacific for a seminar with Guilherme Lichand.\n\nStanford affiliates
  are invited to join us at 11:40 AM for lunch\, prior to the seminar.  The 
 Winter Seminar Series continues through March\; see our Winter Seminar Seri
 es page for speakers and topics. Sign up for our newsletter for announcemen
 ts. \n\nAbout the Seminar:\n\nA rapidly expanding literature documents the 
 detrimental effects of excessive cell phone use\, particularly on mental he
 alth outcomes and attention. While nearly all studies focus on adult popula
 tions\, many experts have used them to support phone bans in schools – part
 ially in the hope that these might help reverse declining trends in standar
 dized test scores dating from even before the Covid-19 pandemic. This paper
  provides first-hand evidence that phone restrictions in schools indeed cau
 sally boost K–12 learning outcomes. Leveraging the introduction of a policy
  that banned non-pedagogical uses of cell phones within schools in Rio de J
 aneiro\, Brazil\, we contrast schools that already had strict rules on phon
 e use even before the policy (the control group) to all other schools (the 
 treatment group)\, before and after the ban. We find that\, 1.5 year after 
 roll-out\, (1) the prevalence of high-usage schools converged across groups
 \; and (2) standardized test scores significantly increased in treatment sc
 hools\, relative to control: in the former\, students learned 0.06 s.d. mor
 e – enough to fully eliminate the baseline gap in test scores across groups
 .\n\nAbout the Speaker:\n\nGuilherme is an Assistant Professor of Education
  at Stanford\, co-Director at the Stanford Lemann Center for Entrepreneursh
 ip and Educational Innovation in Brazil\, and a faculty affiliate at the St
 anford King Center for Global Development\, the Stanford Center on Early Ch
 ildhood\, the Stanford Institute for Advancing Just Societies\, and the UC 
 Berkeley Center for Effective Global Action. He holds a PhD in Political Ec
 onomy and Government from Harvard University. Previously\, he was the UNICE
 F professor of Economics and Child Wellbeing and Development at the Univers
 ity of Zurich. Guilherme was recognized by the Schwab Foundation and Folha 
 de São Paulo as Brazil's top-10 social entrepreneur (post-pandemic legacy)\
 , in 2020\, and by MIT Technology Review as Brazil's top social innovator a
 mong under-35 entrepreneurs\, in 2014. He is also an expert in social innov
 ation at the World Economic Forum Expert Network.
DTEND:20260210T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083906Z
DTSTART:20260210T200000Z
GEO:37.428476;-122.16909
LOCATION:Building 120\, McClatchy Hall\, Main Quad\, Studio S40 - bring you
 r Stanford ID card/mobile ID to enter the building
SEQUENCE:0
