BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:OverviewJoin us to enhance your clinical approach to evaluating
  and managing hip\, thigh\, and leg pain in active individuals and athletes
 . Expert faculty will review the differential diagnosis of common extra-art
 icular and intra-articular causes of hip pain\, as well as prevalent runnin
 g-related injuries affecting the thigh and lower leg. Learners will review 
 updated approaches to diagnosis and management of these conditions\, incorp
 orating recent advances and evolving concepts in sports medicine care.\n\nR
 egistrationRegistration for all practitioners - free.\n\nTo register for th
 is activity\, please click HERE\n\nCreditsAMA PRA Category 1 Credits™ (1.00
  hours)\, Non-Physician Participation Credit (1.00 hours)\n\nTarget Audienc
 eSpecialties - Internal Medicine\, Primary Care & Population Health\, Sport
 s MedicineProfessions - Non-Physician\, Physician\n ObjectivesAt the conclu
 sion of this activity\, learners should be able to:\n1. Evaluate the non-ar
 thritic hip and on physical exam to differentiate between intra-articular h
 ip pain from extra-articular hip pain\n2. List the differential diagnosis o
 f non-arthritic hip pain\n3. Discuss the differential diagnosis of leg pain
  in the runner\n4. Explain when to refer the patient with nonarthritic hip 
 to the orthopaedist \n5. Develop strategies to treat the different causes o
 f leg pain in the runner\n\nAccreditationIn support of improving patient ca
 re\, Stanford Medicine is jointly accredited by the Accreditation Council f
 or Continuing Medical Education (ACCME)\, the Accreditation Council for Pha
 rmacy Education (ACPE)\, and the American Nurses Credentialing Center (ANCC
 )\, to provide continuing education for the healthcare team. \n \nCredit De
 signation \nAmerican Medical Association (AMA) \nStanford Medicine designat
 es this Live Activity for a maximum of 1.00 AMA PRA Category 1 CreditsTM.  
 Physicians should claim only the credit commensurate with the extent of the
 ir participation in the activity.
