BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:This talk will present the initial findings and methodological 
 questions of the Database of Visitors to the “Museum of Rome” (1733–1870)\,
  which is currently being developed within the research project Visibility 
 Reclaimed. The data\, quantitative and qualitative\, in the process of bein
 g catalogued\, reflect the evolution of the first public museums in Rome in
  relation to the different geographical origins and categories (social\, cu
 ltural\, gender) of the international and cosmopolitan public who directly 
 accessed their collections. In particular\, the talk intends to reflect on 
 methodological questions and the results of early research findings related
  to the multiplicity of sources: requests for visiting\, copying and studyi
 ng museums and ancient monuments\, as well as access registers and visitors
 ’ books of private galleries and collections. At the current stage\, the da
 tabase allows the mapping of artistic presences and trajectories inside the
  “Museum of Rome” during the decades between the 1820s and the 1870s. It pr
 ovides significant data on the networks that fueled the system of education
  for foreign artists and architects in Rome\, enabling new reflections on t
 he controversial relationship between artists and the papal institutions re
 sponsible for the preservation of the city’s artistic and architectural her
 itage. However\, it also reveals gaps and fragmentation of archival sources
 \, that require to be critically considered when analyzing the data.\n\nReg
 ister to join online\n\nLunch will begin at 11:45 a.m. for in-person attend
 ees.\n\nAbout the Speakers\n\nCarla Mazzarelli is an Associate Professor at
  the Institute of the History and Theory of Art and Architecture\, Universi
 tà della Svizzera Italiana. Since 2023\, she has directed the SNSF-funded p
 roject Visibility Reclaimed\, and since 2022\, she has been a Project Partn
 er in the SNSF-funded project The Civility of Anatomy. Her researches focus
  in particular on classical and academic culture between the Seventeenth an
 d Nineteenth centuries\, on the history of collecting and museums\, as well
  as on artistic fruition\, the role of audiences\, and issues relating to t
 he transmission of models and artistic reproducibility from the early moder
 n period to the twentieth century. In 2023 she was a Visiting Research Fell
 ow at Durham University\, and in 2025 she was an Invited Researcher within 
 the DEA Programme at the Foundation de la Maison des sciences de l'Homme in
  Paris. She has also been a fellow of the Paul Mellon Centre-Yale Universit
 y\, the Roberto Longhi Foundation for Art History Studies\, the Accademia d
 i San Luca\, and the British Academy at the Courtauld Institute. In 2024 sh
 e was awarded the Award of Best Teaching  by the Università della Svizzera 
 italiana.\n\nAmong her most recent publications: L’anatomia tra lettere e a
 rti: rappresentazioni e immaginari dal XVI al XXI secolo (with Linda Bisell
 o\; Brill\, Nuncius Series 2025)\, Pubblici dei primi musei pubblici (XVIII
 -XIX sec.). I. Le fonti istituzionali (with G. Capitelli\, C. Piva\, Mendri
 sio Academy Press 2025)\; Leonardo nel Novecento. Arti\, scienze e lettere 
 in dialogo\, (Cinisello Balsamo\, Silvana editoriale 2023. Quale gotico per
  Milano. I materiali della giuria per il concorso della facciata del Duomo 
 (1886-1888)\, (with A. Windholz\, M. Moizi)\, Cinisello Balsamo\, Silvana e
 ditoriale 2023\; Lettere d’artista: per una storia transnazioanale dell’art
 e (XVII-XIX secolo)\, with G. Capitelli\, M.P.Donato\, S.A.Meyer\, I.Miarel
 li Mariani\, Cinisello Balsamo (Mi)\, Silvana\, 2022\; Il carteggio d'artis
 ta. Fonti\, questioni\, ricerche tra XVII e XIX secolo (with S. Rolfi\, Cin
 isello Balsamo 2019)\; Dipingere in copia. Da Roma all'Europa (1750-1870). 
 I. Teorie e pratiche\, Roma\, Campisano 2018\n\nLuca Piccoli is a PhD candi
 date\, within the Research Project Visibility Reclaimed\, at the Institute 
 of the History and Theory of Art and Architecture\, Università della Svizze
 ra italiana. His dissertation\, supervised by Carla Mazzarelli and co-super
 vised by Chiara Piva (Sapienza Università di Roma)\, investigates the origi
 ns of museography in eighteenth-century Rome. He was a fellow at the Swiss 
 Institute in the transdisciplinary program Roma Calling 2024/2025. He is cu
 rrently a Visiting Student Researcher at Stanford University (Department of
  Classics) within the framework of the SNSF Mobility Grant\, from October 2
 025 to March 2026.
