DESCRIPTION:Jeffrey J. Kripal\, J. Newton Rayzor Professor of Philosophy an
 d Religious Thought at Rice University and author of The Superhumanities an
 d How to Think Impossibly\, visits Stanford for two public events exploring
  the intersections of the human\, the superhuman\, and the study of mind an
 d culture.\n \nA Garden Next Door: How One Woman Was Struck by Lightning\, 
 Talked to God\, and Came Back to Dream the Future \nWednesday\, February 11
 \, 2026 | 5:30–7:00 PM | Stanford Humanities Center\, Watt Room and online\
 nRSVP >>\n\nProf. Kripal will discuss his work with Elizabeth Krohn\, who w
 as struck by lightning in the parking lot of her synagogue on September of 
 1988. They have co-authored Changed in a Flash: One Woman’s Near-Death Expe
 rience and How a Scholar Thinks It Empowers Us All (North Atlantic Books\, 
 2018).\n\nThe Humanities Today \nThursday\, February 12\, 2026 | 5:30–7:30 
 PM | Stanford Humanities Center\, Levinthal Hall\n\nA roundtable on why the
  humanities matter\, and how they should change. Lecture followed by respon
 ses from Gabriella Safran (Slavic Languages and Literatures)\, Elaine Fishe
 r (Religious Studies)\, and Matthew Wilson Smith (German Studies)\, moderat
 ed by Amir Eshel (Comparative Literature).\n\nCo-sponsored by the Division 
 of Literatures\, Cultures\, and Languages\; The Contemporary\; Stanford's M
 edical Humanities\; and the Stanford Humanities Center
