BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a BioBlitz!\n\nA bioblitz is a community event to o
 bserve and record as many species as possible within a specific location an
 d time period. As part of Love Data Week\, we'll be using iNaturalist to ga
 ther information on our local biodiversity - around Stanford and the Hopkin
 s Marine Station - to better understand the plants\, animals\, and critters
  that share the campus with us.\n\nIf you're not sure where to start\, chec
 k out some of the themed walks and trails on campus.
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260214
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:BioBlitz 2026
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51507101471687
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/love-data-week-2026-bioblitz
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Fitness/Recreational Sport
DESCRIPTION:Have you ever wanted to do a Triathlon?\n\nJoin in the fun and 
 challenge of one of the best collegiate triathlons in Northern California. 
 The race features a 750m open-water swim\, a 20km bike\, and a 5k run and i
 s organized by Stanford's Triathlon Team.\n\nThis year's race will be held 
 at the beautiful Seal Point Park in San Mateo\, California\, with views of 
 the Bay\, the Santa Cruz Mountains\, and the San Francisco Skyline.\n\nThe 
 race is open to beginners and experts alike! We host two race formats: Our 
 classic sprint offers waves for all athletes\, including the option to race
  as a relay team! The draft-legal sprint is a competitive race format for e
 xperienced triathletes and has collegiate\, open\, and elite waves!
DTEND:20260214T220000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260214T160000Z
GEO:37.573403;-122.301077
LOCATION:Seal Point Park
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Treeathlon 2026
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51828774357494
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/treeathlon-2026
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Exhibition
DESCRIPTION:This exhibit showcases capstone projects from "The Senior Refle
 ction" in the Biology Department\, a unique course that asks students to co
 nceive\, produce\, and exhibit a creative project centering around Biology 
 or the life sciences.\n\nCo-founded and taught by Professor Susan McConnell
  and Lecturer Andrew Todhunter\, the course provides a space for students t
 o blend their scientific studies with creative expression\, using media as 
 diverse as painting\, poetry\, needle point\, bookmaking\, and the performi
 ng arts. The projects in this display were created by students in the 2024-
 2025 cohort. \n\nThe exhibit will be on display in Hohbach Hall in Green Li
 brary for the duration of the Winter 2026 quarter.
DTEND:20260214T180000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260214T170000Z
GEO:37.426631;-122.167086
LOCATION:Hohbach Hall\, Entrance
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Undergraduate Showcase: The Senior Reflection in Biology
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51818353479534
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/undergraduate-showcase-the-senior-ref
 lection-in-biology
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Social Event/Reception,Other
DESCRIPTION:Volunteers help keep the farm running. Volunteer tasks vary fro
 m week to week. Farm tasks may include keeping our fields free of weeds and
  rocks\, planting new crop rotations\, deadheading flowers\, teaming up on 
 irrigation\, composting\, mulching\, and having a great time getting dirty.
  We ask that volunteers come prepared with close-toed shoes and clothes you
  don't mind getting dirty! We have gloves and tools for all.\n\nWe welcome 
 volunteers 10 years old and older. Those between 10 and 14 years old are re
 quired to have a guardian actively volunteering alongside them for the dura
 tion of the volunteer session.\n\nWe reserve the right to cancel volunteer 
 sessions up to two hours in advance. Possible reasons for cancelation are a
  change in COVID-19 guidelines as outlined by the University or County Offi
 cials\, excessive heat (90 degree and above)\, poor air quality\, rain or o
 ther inclement weather.\n\nWe encourage all volunteers to carpool\, bike\, 
 ride public transportation\; there is a charge for parking on all Stanford 
 property. The farm is not responsible for any tickets incurred while volunt
 eering.\n\nUPON ARRIVAL: ALL VOLUNTEERS MUST COMPLETE A SAFETY WAIVER \n\nW
 HEN YOU ARRIVE AT THE FARM: Complete Waiver Form
DTEND:20260214T193000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260214T173000Z
GEO:37.426059;-122.183261
LOCATION:O'Donohue Educational Farm
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Volunteering at Stanford Educational Farm
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51288078566322
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/copy-of-volunteering-at-the-stanford-
 educational-farm
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Exhibition
DESCRIPTION:Cunning Folk considers magical practice\, practitioners\, and t
 heir persecution in early modern European artwork and material culture (c.1
 500–1750). The term “cunning folk” typically describes wise people who knew
  traditional spells and remedies believed to cure and protect. The works on
  paper\, painting\, and personal items on view in this intimate\, single ga
 llery exhibition more broadly explore the historical concept of “cunning” i
 n connection to many forms of secret magical rites and knowledge\, from fol
 k charms to occult natural philosophy to diabolic witchcraft. Early modern 
 artists also helped construct the idea of magical figures as a threat to th
 e prevailing social order–particularly through the rise of print culture–an
 d here\, a selection of American contemporary artworks reconjure these hist
 ories.\n\nThis exhibition is organized by the Cantor Arts Center and curate
 d by Sara Lent Frier\, Burton and Deedee McMurtry Assistant Curator\, Print
 s\, Drawings\, and Academic Engagement. We gratefully acknowledge sustained
  support for Cunning Folk: Witchcraft\, Magic\, and Occult Knowledge provid
 ed by The Halperin Exhibitions Fund.\n\nIMAGE: Dominique Viviant Denon (Fre
 nch\, 1747–1825)\, A Coven of Witches (detail)\, 18th century. Etching. Can
 tor Arts Center\, Stanford University\, gift of William Drummond\, 2019. Va
 riable channel video installation (color\, sound)\; 2:50 min. Cantor Arts C
 enter\, Stanford University\, The Anonymous B Acquisitions Fund © Jeffrey G
 ibson\n\nMUSEUM HOURS\nWed & Fri: 11 AM–6 PM\nThurs: 11 AM–8 PM\nSat & Sun:
  10 AM–5 PM\nCLOSED: Mon and Tues\nWe’re always free! Come visit us\, https
 ://museum.stanford.edu/visit
DTEND:20260215T020000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260214T190000Z
GEO:37.432981;-122.170494
LOCATION:Cantor Arts Center\, Ruth Levison Halperin Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Cunning Folk: Witchcraft\, Magic\, and Occult Knowledge
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50605114930108
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/cunning-folk-witchcraft-magic-and-occ
 ult-knowledge
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Tour
DESCRIPTION:This exhibition celebrates Auguste Rodin’s relentless pursuit t
 o convey complex emotions\, diverse psychological states\, and pure sensual
 ity through the nude. A century after his death\, Auguste Rodin continues t
 o be recognized for making figurative sculpture modern by redefining the ex
 pressive capacity of the human form. IMAGE: Auguste Rodin (France\, 1840–19
 17)\, The Age of Bronze (L’Âge d’airain)\, 1875-1876. Bronze\, cast c. 1920
 . Gift of the B. Gerald Cantor Collection\, 1983.300\n\nPublic Tours: Frida
 ys and Saturdays at 11:30am\n\nAdmission Info\n\nTours do not require a res
 ervation and are free of charge.\n\nFirst come\, first served!
