BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:Abstract\n\nGeologic hydrogen\, including both naturally occurr
 ing and stimulated\, is a promising primary energy resource. The Earth is a
  natural laboratory where hydrogen can be observed from surface features (e
 .g.\, springs\, fairy circles) and subsurface structures (e.g. geothermal w
 ells\, chromite mines). The Earth is also a natural factory where both natu
 ral and stimulated hydrogen can be generated through water–rock reactions s
 uch as serpentinization -- a highly complex set of coupled chemo-mechanical
  processes (Hu\, 2025a). The development of geologic hydrogen can be accele
 rated significantly by leveraging decades of technologies developed in indu
 stries such as geothermal (Hu et al.\, 2026)\, with a key distinction of H2
  generation.\n\nIn this talk\, Hu will present several major factors that c
 ontrol the economics of stimulated geologic hydrogen: the efficiency of H₂ 
 extraction and injection strategies\, stress-mediated reaction rates\, frac
 ture density\, and water consumption and regional water availability. First
 \, a novel cyclic injection approach that enhances H₂ extraction will be in
 troduced. This technology exploits the interplay between two-phase flow and
  fracture geometry and has been tested using both numerical modeling and la
 boratory experiments.\n\nTo investigate the chemo-mechanical controls on H₂
  generation\, a previously developed modeling framework\, NMM–Crunch (Hu et
  al.\, 2021)\, has been extended to account for stress-mediated mineral dis
 solution and growth within a new unified chemo-mechanical rate law. The mod
 el has been applied to simulate H₂ generation in partially serpentinized ro
 cks and it demonstrates that stress suppresses serpentinization reactions\,
  thereby reducing H₂ generation rates.\n\nFinally\, using H₂ generation rat
 es obtained from experiments (Hu\, 2025b) at different temperatures with va
 rying fracture densities and across multiple length scales\, Hu conducted a
  techno-economic analysis of stimulated geologic hydrogen for two potential
  sites in CA with different water supply scenarios. The results show that r
 eaction rates\, controlled primarily by fracture density\, as well as regio
 nal water availability and supply\, are both critical factors governing the
  cost of stimulated geologic hydrogen. These findings highlight key interdi
 sciplinary research areas needed for the future success of geologic hydroge
 n.\n\n \n\nBio\n\nDr. Mengsu Hu is a Staff Scientist at the Lawrence Berkel
 ey National Laboratory. Her research focuses on multiscale numerical modeli
 ng and machine learning for analyzing coupled thermal-hydro-mechanical-chem
 ical (THMC) processes from fundamental Earth science to subsurface engineer
 ing systems. Since 2024\, Dr. Hu has led multiple projects on geologic hydr
 ogen\, studying cyclic injection for economic and seismic safe geologic hyd
 rogen generation and production (funded by ARPA-E)\, anisotropic stress con
 trol on serpentinization (funded by BES)\, and pathways from enhanced geoth
 ermal systems to stimulated geologic hydrogen (newly funded by GTO). Dr. Hu
  is serving on the Board of Directors of American Rock Mechanics Associatio
 n (ARMA). Since 2022\, she has been invited to serve on the Editorial Board
  for Rock Mechanics and Rock Engineering (Associate Editor)\, PNAS Nexus of
  the National Academy of Sciences (NAS)\, Journal of Rock Mechanics and Geo
 technical Engineering\, International Journal of Rock Mechanics and Mining 
 Sciences\, and Geomechanics and Geophysics for Geo-Energy and Geo-Resources
 . In 2022\, Dr. Hu was selected as a participant of National Academy of Eng
 ineering (NAE) U.S. Frontiers of Engineering (FOE) symposium.\n\n \n\nResea
 rch/Related Papers\n\nHu\, M. (2025a). Geologic hydrogen production: Geomec
 hanics\, reactive fluid transport\, and induced seismicity. In Frontiers in
  Geologic Hydrogen\, National Academies Meeting. Link\n\nHu\, M.\, Schill\,
  E.\, Rutqvist\, J.\, Steefel\, C.\, & Weber\, A. (2026). From enhanced geo
 thermal systems (EGS) to stimulated geologic hydrogen. DOE GTO Report\, Law
 rence Berkeley National Laboratory\, Berkeley\, CA.\n\nHu\, M.\, Steefel\, 
 C. I.\, & Rutqvist\, J. (2021). Microscale mechanical–chemical modeling of 
 granular salt: Insights for creep. Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid E
 arth\, 126(12)\, e2021JB023112.\nhttps://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/do
 i/full/10.1029/2021JB023112\n\nHu\, M. (2025b). Toward economic and seismic
 -safe geologic hydrogen. October 10\, 2025\, Warren Distinguished Lecture S
 eries\, University of Minnesota\, Minneapolis\, MN\, United States.\nhttps:
 //cse.umn.edu/cege/events/toward-economic-and-seismic-safe-geologic-hydroge
 n
