BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:Congressman Jim Clyburn (D-SC) will be interviewed by Congressm
 an Ro Khanna (D-CA) regarding Congressman Clyburn’s powerful\, inspirationa
 l new book\, The First Eight: A Personal History of the Pioneering Black Co
 ngressmen Who Shaped a Nation. Congressman Clyburn shares these men’s stori
 es\, as they pursued America’s great promise of equality for all. Through t
 he trials\, triumphs\, and challenges that all nine men faced\, Congressman
  Clyburn reveals an insightful new way of understanding the complex period 
 between the Civil War and the present\, one that until now has buried their
  life stories. Their story is our story\, offering the lessons of history t
 o help propel us into a more just and equitable future.\n\nThis event is co
 -sponsored by the Martin Luther King\, Jr. Research and Education Institute
 \, Stanford Center for Racial Justice\, Department of African and African A
 merican Studies\, and Stanford in Government.
DTEND:20260219T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260219T000000Z
GEO:37.423877;-122.167441
LOCATION:Law School\, Room 290
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The First Eight: A Fireside chat with Congressman Jim Clyburn
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52013838975980
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/the-first-eight
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Film/Screening
DESCRIPTION:She spearheaded some of the greatest battles for women’s and ga
 y rights. A brilliant and sexy superstar who inspired thousands. So how com
 e you never heard of Sally Gearhart?\n\nSally! highlights the life and lega
 cy of Sally Gearhart—a charismatic\, trailblazing lesbian-feminist\, activi
 st\, professor\, and fantasy author. Balancing humor\, insight\, and heart\
 , the film is at once a celebration of a radical icon\, a glimpse into quee
 r life and culture in 1970s and 80s San Francisco\; a meditation on the ten
 sions inherent in revolutionary moments\, and a powerful reflection on the 
 lessons her work offers for today’s struggles for civil rights\, justice\, 
 and equality.\n\n“Funny\, provocative\, and deeply moving” – The Boston Glo
 be\n\nAbout the filmmaker Deborah Craig:\n\nDeborah Craig is an award-winni
 ng documentary director and producer whose films use compelling personal st
 ories to raise awareness about the challenges and strengths of underreprese
 nted communities. Sally!—her first feature-length documentary—premiered in 
 2024 and has since screened at over 50 festivals in the U.S. and around the
  globe. \n\nRSVP here!
DTEND:20260219T030000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083907Z
DTSTART:20260219T010000Z
GEO:37.427405;-122.1697
LOCATION:Building 160\, Wallenberg Hall\, 4th Floor
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Sally! Film Screening & Filmmaker Talk
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51834794050036
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/sally-film-screening-director-talk
