BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:We are delighted to host Radhika Koul (Literature\, Claremont M
 cKenna). We can also look forward to a response from Shu-han Luo (English\,
  UC Berkeley).\n\nKoul argues that literature's capacity to reproduce emoti
 on across time\, space\, and culture—an anachronistic phenomenon underackno
 wledged in literary criticism—must be embraced as a methodologically produc
 tive foundation for comparative literary critique. She contends that this s
 hared experiential subjectivity\, in which thought and feeling are insepara
 ble\, justifies conversation as a critical comparative methodology: one tha
 t is creatively anachronistic\, affectively sensitive\, and\, in Eric Hayot
 's phrase\, "open to the world." Such a methodology circumvents two of the 
 most naturalized organizing principles of Anglophone literary study—nationa
 l literary history as the primary horizon of analysis and periodization as 
 the container of literary production. In their place\, these conversations 
 constitute what Rocco Rubini\, invoking the hermeneutist Emilio Betti\, cal
 ls the "communion of the living and the dead": humanism enacted as ongoing 
 practice rather than static doctrine\, generating unstable but generative s
 paces of discovery that are irreducibly present and personal to the critic 
 mediating them. Like the best conversations\, they produce a remainder—cons
 ider the estrangement that arises when Abhinavagupta is brought to bear on 
 Hamlet\, a reading briefly demonstrated here. Both the exchange and its est
 rangement constitute a leveling of the playing field\, which is precisely w
 here the postcolonial payoff of such a praxis lies. By treating this shared
  subjectivity as legitimate ground for conversation\, we create conditions 
 for a more equitable\, more human\, and more humanistic literary criticism—
 one that cannot relegate non-Western traditions to the margins and makes pr
 eviously unthinkable exchanges not only licit but productive. The article p
 roceeds in three movements: first\, distinguishing empathic from hegemonic 
 universals\; second\, recovering historical precedents in critics working b
 efore the "temporalization of history"\; and third\, outlining conversation
 's defining characteristics as critical practice.\n\nThis event is hosted b
 y Comparative Methodologies\, a research group in the DLCL Research Unit. P
 lease write to Harry (harrycar@stanford.edu) with any questions. We hope to
  see you there! \n\nRSVP HERE for Comparative Methodologies Event
DTEND:20260220T213000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083908Z
DTSTART:20260220T200000Z
GEO:37.427405;-122.1697
LOCATION:Building 260\, Pigott Hall\, Room 216
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Comparative Methodologies: On Conversation as Method
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52075406388586
