BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk,Meeting
DESCRIPTION:This month we are joined by Ayako Kawano\, a PhD candidate in t
 he Emmett Interdisciplinary Program in Environment and Resources at Stanfor
 d. Ayako’s research examines the impact of air pollution on population heal
 th and climate change in low- and middle-income countries using remote sens
 ing data and machine learning methods. Ayako recently won the Stanford Univ
 ersity Libraries Data Sharing Prize for her work publishing a long-term dat
 aset of fine particulate matter concentrations in India\, which has been us
 ed to inform public health programs and policy as well as used in further r
 esearch projects.\n\nAbout the Bay Area Open Science Group\nThe Bay Area Op
 en Science Group is a growing community for Bay Area academics and research
 ers interested in incorporating open science into their research\, teaching
 \, and learning. Targeting students\, faculty\, and staff at UCSF\, Berkele
 y\, and Stanford\, the goal of the community is to increase awareness of an
 d engagement with all things open science\, including open access articles\
 , open research data\, open source software\, and open educational resource
 s. Through this work the group hopes to connect researchers with tools they
  can use to make the products and process of science more equitable and rep
 roducible.
DTEND:20260224T230000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083908Z
DTSTART:20260224T220000Z
