BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:This workshop offers an insight into chronicles as a central fo
 rm of medieval historiography. Using examples from the Stanford collections
 \, different types of chronicles are presented\, with a focus on German-lan
 guage world chronicles and city chronicles. Concrete examples are used to s
 how how chronicles combine very heterogeneous fields of knowledge\, such as
  biblical history\, historical world events\, local events\, and ancient my
 thology. In this way\, the workshop also provides insights into the underst
 anding of history in the Middle Ages\, in which historical events are not o
 nly documented but are contextualized within Christian history of salvation
 .\n\nA special focus is placed on working with original materials: particip
 ants will have the opportunity to examine various chronicles up close. Thes
 e include copies of the famous Schedelsche Weltchronik or Nuremberg Chronic
 le (1493)\, one of the most important printed works of the late 15th centur
 y.\n\nProf. Margit Dahm is Assistant Professor of Early German Literature o
 f the High and Late Middle Ages in the Department of Early German Literatur
 e at Kiel University.
DTEND:20260227T200000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083908Z
