BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:PhD Defense
DESCRIPTION:Abstract\nSeismometers continuously record ground motion. Signa
 ls from natural hazards\, such as earthquakes and volcanic eruptions\, howe
 ver\, contribute only a small portion of seismograms. The rest is the so-ca
 lled seismic ambient noise. The same concept also applies to infrasound dat
 a\, which record pressure fluctuations at the surface. In fact\, these ambi
 ent signals reflect the evolution of natural processes and can contribute t
 o a rich dataset for environmental studies.\n\nMy dissertation analyzes sig
 natures in ambient seismoacoustic signals associated with two atmospheric p
 henomena: hurricane boundary-layer turbulence and tropospheric inertia-grav
 ity waves. These analyses are made possible by the rich data recorded by th
 e Transportable Array\, a nationwide multi-instrument seismic station netwo
 rk. I explain how we can leverage the advantages of this seismic station ne
 twork to complement atmospheric observations.\n\nIn the first part\, I expl
 ain the turbulent seismoacoustic imprints during the landfall of Hurricane 
 Isaac at the Gulf Coast in August 2012 through an interdisciplinary modelin
 g framework. It combines large-eddy simulation of hurricane boundary layer 
 turbulence with the subsequent quasi-static elastic response of the ground.
  I further present the use of infrasound data as a proxy for near-surface w
 ind speed and its application to measure from pressure spectra the turbulen
 t dissipation rate\, an important turbulent statistic parameterized in hurr
 icane models. These complement land-based in situ hurricane observations fr
 om portable wind towers and weather stations.\n\nIn the second part\, I sea
 rch for signals of tropospheric inertia-gravity waves\, i.e.\, long-period 
 atmospheric internal gravity waves in the troposphere\, using four years of
  barometric pressure data from the Transportable Array. I develop workflows
  based on array processing techniques to identify coherent signals among st
 ation triads and measure their apparent horizontal phase velocity. The data
 base contains ~70\,000 measurements of wave parameters at station triads. I
 t shows higher wave activity during winter\, and the dominant eastward prop
 agation direction is linked to the influence of background winds. Observati
 on of these mesoscale waves can contribute to high-resolution datasets for 
 meteorological studies.
DTEND:20260227T200000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083908Z
DTSTART:20260227T190000Z
GEO:37.426402;-122.172635
LOCATION:Mitchell Earth Sciences\, 350/372
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Geophysics PhD Defense\, Qing Ji: "Atmospheric signatures in ambien
 t seismoacoustic signals"
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52137086640453
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/geophysics-phd-defense-qing-ji-atmosp
 heric-signatures-in-ambient-seismoacoustic-signals
