BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:PhD Defense
DESCRIPTION:Through the growth of compute power\, high-fidelity simulations
  have become increasingly accessible and gained widespread adoption in acad
 emics and industry. Understanding physical phenomena\, prediction and other
  design stages rely heavily on CFD. The cornerstone of these numerical simu
 lations is the efficient use of parallel\, distributed algorithms\, often t
 uned to hardware specific microarchitectures for maximum performance. To le
 verage regular data indexing for faster memory access and    optimized layo
 ut\, structured multiblock grids arise as a natural choice. Combined with c
 urvilinear transformations\, this topological framework enhances solver fid
 elity by allowing for precise control over mesh density in critical regions
 \, while maintaining the flexibility to resolve complex geometries.
DTEND:20260227T210000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083909Z
DTSTART:20260227T200000Z
GEO:37.427405;-122.1697
LOCATION:Building 260\, Pigott Hall\, Room 113
