BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:
DESCRIPTION:Bringing together neuroscience and computational perspectives\,
  the 2026 MBCT symposium explores how recurrence may be a canonical neural 
 mechanism for integrating past experience\, present input\, and future goal
 s across multiple behavioral timescales.\n\nEvery given moment of our lives
  is some combination of past\, present\, and future. While we occupy the cu
 rrent moment\, we integrate sensory information from the recent past\, draw
  on relevant memories from more distant experience\, anticipate upcoming ev
 ents\, and make goal-directed decisions that guide our actions. \n\nWhat ar
 e the neural mechanisms underlying our brain's ability to coordinate inform
 ation from such different timescales?\n\nIn neuroscience\, recurrent feedba
 ck has long been known to link the recent past and the present by allowing 
 neuronal computations to be affected not just by current sensory input\, bu
 t by recurrent patterns of activity from the recent past. To what degree is
  such recurrent computation a canonical motif of neural computation that al
 lows our brains to integrate multiple timescales required for behavior? In 
 this symposium\, we explore emerging views of behaviors that unfold over di
 fferent timescales\, and how recurrent neural computation can support these
  behaviors.\n\nSign up to receive future updates about the symposium and ad
 ditional events\n\nMBCT Symposium 2026 - Featured SpeakersSpeakerInstitutio
 nTalk TitleJanice Chen\n\nJohns Hopkins University\n\nStudying memory for n
 atural events across multiple timescalesHidehiko Inagaki\n\nMax Planck Flor
 ida Institute for Neuroscience\n\nPerturbation experiments to dissect attra
 ctor dynamics for flexible motor timingCaroline A. Runyan\n\nUniversity of 
 Pittsburgh\n\nState-dependent population codes across cortexKohitij KarYork
  UniversityComputational model-guided insights into temporal dynamics of th
 e macaque ventral stream
DTEND:20260305T020000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083909Z
DTSTART:20260304T210000Z
LOCATION:Stanford Neurosciences Building | John A. and Cynthia Fry Gunn Rot
 unda\, E241
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:MBCT Symposium 2026: Linking Timescales of Behavior and Neural Acti
 vity through Recurrent Computation
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51910619143311
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/mbct-symposium-2026-linking-timescale
 s-of-behavior-and-neural-activity-through-recurrent-computation
END:VEVENT
