CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:Abstract: Andrey will discuss two active research areas at the 
 intersection of economics and AI. First\, Fradkin draws on their work about
  the market for LLMs to outline the open questions regarding competition am
 ong models\, creators\, and providers. Second\, they will discuss the idea 
 of a Coasean Singularity and some barriers to existing agentic technologies
  in fulfilling this ideal. Throughout\, Fradkin poses open questions that w
 e should be working on as a community.\n\nSpeaker: Andrey Fradkin\, Associa
 te Professor of Marketing\, Boston University Questrom School of Business\;
  Economics of AI\, Amazon (on leave)\n\nSpeaker Bio: Andrey Fradkin is an a
 ssociate professor of marketing at the Boston University Questrom School of
  Business and an affiliate of the Boston University Economics Department\, 
 currently on leave working on the economics of AI at Amazon. His research f
 ocuses on the economics of digital markets and AI\, quantitative marketing\
 , and search and matching markets\, and has been published in top marketing
 \, economics\, and computer science outlets. He has provided expert input o
 n the digital economy to the President's Council on Science and Technology 
 and the Federal Trade Commission. He worked as a data scientist at Airbnb w
 hile completing his Ph.D. in Economics at Stanford University. He co-hosts 
 the podcast Justified Posteriors.\n\nThe logistics details for each session
  will be provided to registered participants.  Sign up here to be included 
 on the mailing list and learn about future events.\n\nThis talk is co-spons
 ored by USF's Master's in Applied Economics and the Stanford Causal Science
  Center. For additional information and abstracts from past talks\, please 
 click here. \n\nThe BATES events are completely free to attend. If you’d li
 ke to support future events and our research\, please consider making a gif
 t to Stanford Data Science: https://bit.ly/supportSDS.
DTEND:20260306T043000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083909Z
