BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:The Stanford Cancer Institute Breakthroughs in Cancer seminar s
 eries is one of the highest-profile seminar series for translational and cl
 inical scientists in oncology. The series brings national leaders in cancer
  research to Stanford’s campus and highlights innovations across the spectr
 um of basic\, translational\, clinical\, and population science. \n\nJoin u
 s Tuesday\, March 10\, 4-5 p.m.\, at Munzer Auditorium\, Beckman Center\, o
 r Zoom for a presentation by Reuben Shaw\, PhD\, director of the Salk Insti
 tute Cancer Center. \n\nDr. Shaw’s research has been instrumental in defini
 ng how tumor suppressor and oncogene signaling pathways interact to regulat
 e cellular metabolism. His lab discovered that LKB1\, a gene frequently mut
 ated in cancer\, regulates the AMPK enzyme\, establishing the LKB1–AMPK pat
 hway as a central energy-sensing mechanism that reprograms cell growth and 
 metabolism under nutrient stress. His lab has focused on how various kinase
 s sense changes in cellular energy and coordinate that with mitochondrial f
 unction and turnover. His work has illuminated how exercise\, diet\, and me
 tformin suppress diabetes and cancer\, and has helped identify therapeutic 
 strategies targeting metabolic vulnerabilities in cancer.The event is open 
 to Stanford Cancer Institute members\, postdocs\, fellows\, and students\, 
 as well as Stanford University and Stanford Medicine faculty\, trainees\, a
 nd staff interested in basic\, translational\, clinical\, and population-ba
 sed cancer research.\n\nRegistration is encouraged.
DTEND:20260311T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083910Z
DTSTART:20260310T230000Z
