BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk,Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Carlotta Wright de la Cal will workshop her dissertation chapte
 r in progress\, "Rails of Rebellion: Infrastructure\, Law\, and Indigenous 
 Mobility in the Sonora-Arizona Borderlands\, 1880-1930."\n\nPaper abstract:
  This dissertation chapter in progress examines the use of labor migration 
 by Indigenous communities at the turn of the twentieth century. During this
  period\, Wright de la Cal argues\, Yaqui workers in the Arizona-Sonora bor
 derlands strategically leveraged labor in extractive industries to sustain 
 communities\, evade state surveillance\, and support anticolonial resistanc
 e in the face of Mexican state genocide and U.S. immigration restriction. F
 ocusing on the railroad and mining industries\, this chapter explores how Y
 aqui laborers embedded community into infrastructure designed for disposses
 sion. Drawing on Mexican Foreign Affairs archives\, U.S. Immigration and Na
 turalization Service records\, Southern Pacific corporate files\, and oral 
 histories\, this chapter is part of a larger dissertation on railroad labor
  and migration.
DTEND:20260311T213000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083910Z
DTSTART:20260311T200000Z
