BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:
DESCRIPTION:Estonians and Finns are separated by the Baltic Sea but have cl
 ose linguistic and cultural ties which persevered throughout the Cold War. 
 At the end of the 1980s these blossomed into a wave of Finnish aid which no
 t only alleviated economic woes inherent to the Soviet system\, but took on
  a political dimension by kindling the fire of pro-independence movements i
 n Estonia. Person-to-person informal networks which moved vast amounts of c
 lothing\, medicine\, technology\, toys and food from independent Finland to
  Soviet Estonia gave recipients a real “taste” of freedom even before the f
 all of the Iron Curtain. These networks enabled individual families in Esto
 nia not only to survive but to thrive within the precarious economic enviro
 nment that defined the last years of Soviet rule. Although taste\, smell\, 
 flavor and their social constructs have traditionally been ignored in polit
 ical histories\, there is no denying that a sort of "sensual turn" has take
 n place in the 21st century. The echoes of the olfactory as well as materia
 l encounters between Estonians and Finns can be still heard in modern day e
 xperiences and routines as well as Estonia’s political culture\, which sets
  Estonia apart from many other former Soviet states.\n\nPlease RSVP here.\n
 \nMaarja Merivoo-Parro is dedicated to exploring the history of mentality a
 t the crossroads of culture and politics and has extensive field work exper
 ience among Estonian communities from Abkhazia to Australia. She is a Fulbr
 ight scholar and currently holds the position of Marie Curie fellow at the 
 University of Jyväskylä in Finland. Maarja has received national recognitio
 n for her work as a public intellectual bridging academia and society throu
 gh documentary films\, television and radio programs.
DTEND:20260313T200000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083910Z
DTSTART:20260313T190000Z
GEO:37.426792;-122.164842
LOCATION:Encina Commons\, Rm. 123
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:The Taste of Freedom\, the Smell of Democracy: Cold War Spontaneous
  Humanitarian Aid from Finland to Estonia
