BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Conference/Symposium
DESCRIPTION:OverviewStanford Otology Update 2026 is designed to advance the
  knowledge and clinical skills of healthcare providers specializing in adul
 t and pediatric otologic disorders. This comprehensive program will focus o
 n the latest advances in the diagnosis\, medical management\, and surgical 
 treatment of common and complex ear conditions. Participants will gain prac
 tical insights into risk reduction strategies\, effective ordering and inte
 rpretation of diagnostic tests\, and the application of evidence-based prac
 tices to improve patient outcomes. The course consists of a blend of didact
 ic lectures\, interactive panel discussions\, real-word case studies\, and 
 hands-on skills sessions led by expert faculty.\n\nRegistrationAll three da
 ys which includes three hands-on skills session on Saturday\, March 14\, 20
 26. \n\nNEW THIS YEAR FOR AUDIOLOGISTS\nThere will be an all day Audiology 
 program included with your registration - space is limited.\n\nPhysicians: 
 $945.00\nAudiologists\, RN\, PA\, SLP & Residents: $300.00\nStanford Audiol
 ogists/Staff: $0.00 (Must register with Stanford email address)\nCalifornia
  Fellows/Residents ONLY - $0.00 (Must email svittori@stanford.edu for disco
 unt code)\n\nClick HERE to submit your challenging cases panel discussion. 
 Please submit a brief description of the case\, remove all PHI and label th
 e document(s) beginning with your last name.\n\nPlease rank the hands-on se
 ssions you'd like to attend during the registration process.  We will do be
 st to accommodate your request.  You will be able to attend 3 sessions on S
 aturday\, March 14\, 2026. \n\nHands On Sessions Include:\nEndoscopic Ear S
 urgery/Ossiculoplasty\nImplantable Devices (limit 10 learners per session)\
 nVestibular Assessment and Physical Therapy\nOtologic Imaging\nOffice Manag
 ement of Otologic Disorders\nAudiology: Speech in Noise Update:  The Presen
 t & Future\nAudiology: AI in Audiology Panel\nAudiology: Lightening Rounds:
   Hearing Aids & Cochlear Implants\n\nCreditsAMA PRA Category 1 Credits™ (1
 8.75 hours)\, AAPA Category 1 CME credits (18.75 hours)\, ABOHNS MOC Part I
 I (18.75 hours)\, ANCC Contact Hours (18.75 hours)\, Non-Physician Particip
 ation Credit (18.75 hours)\n\nTarget AudienceSpecialties - Otolaryngology (
 ENT)Professions - Advance Practice Nurse (APN)\, Fellow/Resident\, Nurse\, 
 Physician\, Physician Associate\, Registered Nurse (RN)\, Speech Language P
 athologist\, Student ObjectivesAt the conclusion of this activity\, learner
 s should be able to:\n1. Diagnose hearing loss and balance disorders based 
 on specific patient characteristic and practice setting\n2. Develop skills 
 in understanding\, selecting\, and performing otologic surgical procedures\
 n3. Apply risk reduction techniques in otologic surgery to reduce clinical 
 errors\n4. Develop strategies to optimally establish and perform multi-spec
 ialty approach care for complex otologic disorders\n\nAccreditationIn suppo
 rt of improving patient care\, Stanford Medicine is jointly accredited by t
 he Accreditation Council for Continuing Medical Education (ACCME)\, the Acc
 reditation Council for Pharmacy Education (ACPE)\, and the American Nurses 
 Credentialing Center (ANCC)\, to provide continuing education for the healt
 hcare team. \n\nCredit Designation \nAmerican Medical Association (AMA) \nS
 tanford Medicine designates this Live Activity for a maximum of 18.75 AMA P
 RA Category 1 CreditsTM.  Physicians should claim only the credit commensur
 ate with the extent of their participation in the activity. \n\nAmerican Nu
 rses Credentialing Center (ANCC) \nStanford Medicine designates this [inser
 t learning format] activity for a maximum of 18\,75 ANCC contact hours. \n 
 \nAmerican Academy of Physician Associates (AAPA) - Live \nStanford Medicin
 e has been authorized by the American Academy of PAs (AAPA) to award AAPA C
 ategory 1 CME credit for activities planned in accordance with AAPA CME Cri
 teria. This live activity is designated for 18.75 AAPA Category 1 CME credi
 ts. PAs should only claim credit commensurate with the extent of their part
 icipation.  \n\nAmerican Board of Otolaryngology – Head and Neck Surgery MO
 C Credit\nSuccessful completion of this CME activity\, which includes parti
 cipation in the evaluation component\, enables the participant to earn thei
 r required annual part II self-assessment credit in the American Board of O
 tolaryngology – Head and Neck Surgery’s Continuing Certification program (f
 ormerly known as MOC). It is the CME activity provider's responsibility to 
 submit participant completion information to ACCME for the purpose of recog
 nizing participation.
DTSTAMP:20260308T083910Z
