BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:OverviewNavigating nutrition and supplementation can be challen
 ging for young athletes and their families. This session provides practical
 \, evidence-based guidance on sports nutrition for pediatric and adolescent
  athletes\, including key nutrition considerations during clinic visits\, c
 ommonly used supplements\, use cases for creatine and protein powder\, and 
 when a visit to a registered dietitian is appropriate. Join us to gain prac
 tical strategies to support safe and healthy nutrition practices in youth a
 thletes.\n\nRegistrationRegistration is required.\n\nAll practitioners: fre
 e.\n\nCreditsAMA PRA Category 1 Credits™ (1.00 hours)\, BOC Category A Hour
 s/CEUs (1.00 hours)\, Non-Physician Participation Credit (1.00 hours)\, Occ
 upational Therapy Contact Hours (1.00 hours)\, Physical Therapy Contact Hou
 rs (1.00 hours)\n\nTarget AudienceSpecialties - Orthopedics & Sports Medici
 neProfessions - Athletic Trainer\, Fellow/Resident\, Non-Physician\, Occupa
 tional Therapist\, Physical Therapist\, Physician ObjectivesAt the conclusi
 on of this activity\, learners should be able to:\n1. Discuss key sports nu
 trition considerations to address during pediatric and adolescent health vi
 sits.\n2. Describe commonly used dietary supplements that youth athletes an
 d their families frequently inquire about.\n3. Summarize the current eviden
 ce\, indications\, and limitations related to the use of creatine and prote
 in supplementation in youth athletes. 4. Discuss when referral to a registe
 red dietitian is indicated for youth athletes.\n\nAccreditationIn support o
 f improving patient care\, Stanford Medicine is jointly accredited by the A
 ccreditation Council for Continuing Medical Education (ACCME)\, the Accredi
 tation Council for Pharmacy Education (ACPE)\, and the American Nurses Cred
 entialing Center (ANCC)\, to provide continuing education for the healthcar
 e team. \n \nCredit Designation \nAmerican Medical Association (AMA) \nStan
 ford Medicine designates this Live Activity for a maximum of 1.00 AMA PRA C
 ategory 1 CreditsTM.  Physicians should claim only the credit commensurate 
 with the extent of their participation in the activity. \n\nBoard of Certif
 ication\, Inc (BOC)\nStanford Medicine (BOC AP# 0000751) is approved by the
  Board of Certification\, Inc. to provide continuing education to Athletic 
 Trainers (ATs). This program is eligible for a maximum of 1.00 Category A h
 ours/CEUs. ATs should claim only those hours actually spent in the educatio
 nal program.\n\nStanford Health Care Department of Rehabilitation is an app
 roved provider for physical therapy and occupational therapy for courses th
 at meet the requirements set forth by the respective California Boards. Thi
 s course is approved for 1.00 hour CEU for PT and OT.
DTEND:20260314T160000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083911Z
DTSTART:20260314T150000Z
