CATEGORIES:Class/Seminar
DESCRIPTION:CAS IHAWG brings together graduate students across humanities d
 isciplines for sustained\, collective writing and scholarly exchange. Hoste
 d by the Center for African Studies\, the group meets weekly to combine dis
 ciplined co-writing sessions with peer-led workshops and a speaker series t
 hat showcases Africanist humanities research. We foster an encouraging\, pr
 oductive environment where members share work-in-progress\, troubleshoot wr
 iting challenges\, and celebrate milestones in their research. Who should c
 onsider joining:\n\nGraduate students whose research engages Africa or the 
 African diaspora in humanities fields\, including DAAAS/DLCL and other area
  studies\, art and art history\, film and media\, comparative literature\, 
 CCSRE\, education\, English\, feminist and gender studies\, musicology\, ph
 ilosophy\, linguistics\, religious studies\, and theater/performance studie
 s. Interdisciplinary and cross-departmental participation is strongly encou
 raged.\n\nAttendance can be regular or occasional to accommodate academic s
 chedules.\n\nClick here to receive meeting notices and event updates. \n\nF
 or questions\, contact Mpho (mmolefe@stanford.edu) or Seyi (jesuseyi@stanfo
 rd.edu).\n\nWe welcome you to join our writing community.
