BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:Advancements in novel molecular biology techniques have enabled
  the development of promising biomarkers for medical and consumer applicati
 ons. Epigenetic modifications have yielded novel biomarkers of exposures\, 
 lifestyle\, and aging\, generating considerable excitement and momentum in 
 both research and industry. However\, these biomarkers suffer from underlyi
 ng biases due to training datasets derived from non-representative populati
 ons. This talk will highlight existing biases and misuses of epigenetic agi
 ng biomarkers\, with a focus on epigenetic age\, a novel measure of biologi
 cal age that is widely utilized in research and now available for direct-to
 -consumer testing. Data on disparities among underrepresented populations w
 ill demonstrate the potential pitfalls of using existing algorithms without
  acknowledging their current limitations.\n\nSponsored by the Research Inst
 itute of CCSRE.
DTEND:20260331T201500Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083912Z
DTSTART:20260331T190000Z
GEO:37.427685;-122.171735
LOCATION:Building 360\, CCSRE Conference Room
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Andres Cardenas\, "Bias and Equitable Use of Epigenetic Biomarkers 
 in Diverse Populations\," in conversation with Daphne Martschenko
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52215194998335
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/andres-cardenas-bias-and-equitable-us
 e-of-epigenetic-biomarkers-in-diverse-populations-in-conversation-with-daph
 ne-martschenko
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk
DESCRIPTION:About the event: The 2011 Fukushima Dai’ichi nuclear disaster w
 as the worst industrial nuclear catastrophe to hit Japan. It was a major ev
 ent\, rated at the highest severity\, which released radioactive elements i
 nto the power plant’s surrounding environment when back-up systems failed a
 nd could not sufficiently cool the nuclear reactors. At least 164\,000 peop
 le were permanently or temporarily displaced. Radioactive Governance offers
  an ethnographic look at how the disaster was handled by Japan. Unlike prio
 r nuclear-related narratives\, such as those surrounding Chernobyl or Hiros
 hima\, which focused on themes of harm\, trauma\, and victimization\, the J
 apanese government consistently put forward a discourse of minimal or no ra
 diation-related dangers\, a gradual bringing home of former evacuees\, a re
 starting of nuclear power plants\, and the promotion of a resilient mindset
  in the face of adversity. This narrative worked to counter other understan
 dings of recovery\, such as those of worried citizens unsuccessfully fighti
 ng for permanent evacuation because they were afraid to go back to their ho
 mes. Providing a rich theorization of how both governments and citizens sha
 pe narratives about catastrophic events\, Radioactive Governance not only d
 isplays how Fukushima became a story of hope and resilience rather than of 
 victimization\, but also how radioactive governance shifted from the nuclea
 r secrecy that characterized the Cold War era to relying on international o
 rganizations and domestic citizens to co-manage the aftermath of disasters.
 \n\nAbout the speaker: Maxime Polleri is an Assistant Professor in the Depa
 rtment of Anthropology at Université Laval and a member of the Graduate Sch
 ool of International Studies. As an anthropologist of technoscience\, he st
 udies the governance of disasters\, waste and misinformation\, with a prima
 ry focus on nuclear topics and a regional expertise on Japan.
DTEND:20260331T211500Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083912Z
DTSTART:20260331T200000Z
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Radioactive Governance: The Politics of Revitalization in Post-Fuku
 shima Japan
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52261347584708
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/radioactive-governance-the-politics-o
 f-revitalization-in-post-fukushima-japan-5663
END:VEVENT
