BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshop
DESCRIPTION:Science is full of metaphors. From black holes "eating" stars\,
  to yeast "cell factories"\, to brain "circuitry" —the language researchers
  use has the power to shape how ideas are received and remembered. Whether 
 you're crafting a grant proposal\, communicating across disciplines\, or bu
 ilding a public profile\, the ability to translate complex research into re
 sonant\, accessible ideas sets strong scientists apart. Over 3 weekly sessi
 ons\, you'll learn how to build a science metaphor from the ground up—notic
 ing the metaphors already embedded in your field\, evaluating what makes th
 em effective or limiting\, and developing your own with intention.You'll\nl
 eave with a sharper communication toolkit and a deeper understanding of how
  language shapes the way your work is understood and valued.\n\nIntensity L
 evel: Mild intensity\n\nMultiple topics are covered at a steady pace\, with
  in-class activities requiring some preparation. Some out-of-class work is 
 required\, and regular in-class participation is expected. Students will de
 velop a moderate level of skill-building during the course.Facilitated by: 
 Kel Haung\, student\n\nDetails: \n\nWhen: April 14\, 21\, 28 (Tuesdays)\, 4
 -6PM\n\nOpen to enrolled graduate students at any stage in any discipline o
 r degree program. Postdocs will be accepted if space is available\, but pri
 ority is given to graduate students.\n\nMetaphors in Science is an in-perso
 n\, three-part workshop. Session dates are Tuesday's April 14\, 21\,28 from
  4-6PM. Space is limited. Due to the workshop’s interactive format\, full p
 articipation in all three sessions is required. Dinner will be served. \n\n
 If you are accepted to this workshop\, you must confirm your place by submi
 tting a Student Participation Fee Agreement\, which authorizes VPGE to char
 ge $50 to your Stanford bill – only if you do not fully participate in the 
 event. You will receive a link to the Agreement and instructions if you are
  offered a place.\n\nApplication deadline: Tuesday\, April 7th @11:59PM PT.
 \n\nApply here
DTEND:20260429T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083913Z
DTSTART:20260428T230000Z
LOCATION:EVGR 144B
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Metaphors in Science: A Researcher's Guide to Communicating Ideas T
 hat Stick
