BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Presentation/Talk,Other
DESCRIPTION:In this in-person session\, an admission officer provides an ov
 erview of Knight-Hennessy Scholars\, the admission process\, and the applic
 ation. The session includes a presentation\, and Knight-Hennessy scholar(s)
  may join to share their experience. \n\nAbout Knight-Hennessy Scholars\n\n
 Knight-Hennessy Scholars is a multidisciplinary\, multicultural graduate sc
 holarship program. Each Knight-Hennessy scholar receives up to three years 
 of financial support to pursue graduate studies at Stanford while participa
 ting in engaging experiences that prepare scholars to be visionary\, courag
 eous\, and collaborative leaders who address complex challenges facing the 
 world.\n\nEligibility\n\nYou are eligible to apply to the 2027 cohort of Kn
 ight-Hennessy Scholars if you earned (or will earn) your bachelor's degree 
 in 2020 or later. For military (active or veteran) applicants\, you are eli
 gible if you earned your bachelor's degree in 2018 or later. Additionally\,
  current Stanford PhD students in the first year of enrollment may apply if
  starting at KHS in the second year of PhD enrollment.\n\nDeadline\n\nThe K
 HS application to join the 2026 cohort is now closed. The KHS application t
 o join the 2027 cohort will open in summer 2026. \n\nParking\n\nParking at 
 Stanford University is free after 4:00 pm Monday-Friday. We recommend you u
 se the Tressider Lot or street parking. Please visit Stanford Transportatio
 n for more information.\n\nYou will receive details on how to join the even
 t by email following registration.
DTEND:20260523T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083914Z
DTSTART:20260522T230000Z
GEO:37.423558;-122.173774
LOCATION:Denning House
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Info session for Knight-Hennessy Scholars
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51934581403697
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/copy-of-info-session-for-knight-henne
 ssy-scholars-5058
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Exhibition
DESCRIPTION:San Francisco Mission District-based artist Ester Hernandez (b.
  1944) is a celebrated Chicana printmaker and storyteller. In iconic works 
 such as Sun Mad\, she weaves incisive commentary with a bold visual languag
 e. This single-gallery presentation highlights a selection of artwork\, wri
 ting\, and other ephemera from the artist’s archive at Stanford Special Col
 lections. These materials reveal that Hernandez’s artwork and sociopolitica
 l convictions have operated in tandem since the very beginning of her caree
 r\, shaped by her family’s background as farmworkers in California’s raisin
  belt and Hernandez’s own life experiences. Stanford acquired Hernandez’s a
 rchive (Special Collections\, M1301) in 2001.\n\nStanford acquired Hernande
 z’s archive (Special Collections\, M1301) in 2001.\n\nArchive Room: Ester H
 ernandez is curated by Jorge Eduardo Sibaja\, Curatorial Assistant. We grat
 efully acknowledge sustained support provided by The Hockwald Fund.\n\nIMAG
 E: Ester Hernandez\, Sun Mad\, 1982. Courtesy of Department of Special Coll
 ections\, Stanford University Libraries. © Ester Hernandez\n\nMUSEUM HOURS\
 nWed & Fri: 11 AM–6 PM\nThurs: 11 AM–8 PM\nSat & Sun: 10 AM–5 PM\nCLOSED: M
 on and Tues\nWe’re always free! Come visit us\, https://museum.stanford.edu
 /visit
DTSTAMP:20260308T083914Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260523
GEO:37.432981;-122.170494
LOCATION:Cantor Arts Center\, Patricia S. Rebele Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Archive Room: Ester Hernandez |Selections from Special Collections 
 at Stanford Libraries
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50605294457843
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/archive-room-ester-hernandez-selectio
 ns-from-special-collections-at-stanford-libraries
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Exhibition
DESCRIPTION:Ruth Asawa (1926–2013) was a Japanese American artist and arts 
 advocate who worked to integrate arts education into the standard curriculu
 m of San Francisco’s public schools. Although Asawa is best known for her l
 ooped-wire sculptures\, Archive Room: Ruth Asawa explores her lifelong dedi
 cation to arts activism through selected projects from the Alvarado School 
 Arts Workshop curriculum\, an artist-in-residence program she cofounded wit
 h architect and fellow parent Sally Woodbridge at Alvarado Elementary Schoo
 l in 1968. The teaching materials\, workshops\, and collaborative projects 
 presented in this compact\, single-gallery presentation explores Asawa’s be
 lief that art is essential to cultivating a fuller sense of self.\n\nStanfo
 rd acquired Asawa’s archive (Special Collections\, M1585) in 2007 with addi
 tional materials arriving in subsequent years. To explore Asawa’s archive o
 nline\, please visit Stanford Libraries’ website.\n\nArchive Room: Ruth Asa
 wa is curated by Kathryn Cua\, Curatorial Assistant\, Asian American Art In
 itiative. We gratefully acknowledge sustained support provided by The Rober
 t Mondavi Family Fund.\n\nIMAGE: Ruth Asawa teaching geometric patterns wit
 h milk cartons\, c. 1981. Courtesy Ruth Asawa Lanier\, Inc.\n\nMUSEUM HOURS
 \nWed & Fri: 11 AM–6 PM\nThurs: 11 AM–8 PM\nSat & Sun: 10 AM–5 PM\nCLOSED: 
 Mon and Tues\nWe’re always free! Come visit us\, https://museum.stanford.ed
 u/visit
DTSTAMP:20260308T083914Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260523
GEO:37.432981;-122.170494
LOCATION:Cantor Arts Center\, Rowland K. Rebele Gallery
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Archive Room: Ruth Asawa | Selections from Special Collections at S
 tanford Libraries
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50605355587108
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/archive-room-ruth-asawa-selections-fr
 om-special-collections-at-stanford-libraries
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Social Event/Reception,Other
DESCRIPTION:Volunteers help keep the farm running. Volunteer tasks vary fro
 m week to week. Farm tasks may include keeping our fields free of weeds and
  rocks\, planting new crop rotations\, deadheading flowers\, teaming up on 
 irrigation\, composting\, mulching\, and having a great time getting dirty.
  We ask that volunteers come prepared with close-toed shoes and clothes you
  don't mind getting dirty! We have gloves and tools for all.\n\nWe welcome 
 volunteers 10 years old and older. Those between 10 and 14 years old are re
 quired to have a guardian actively volunteering alongside them for the dura
 tion of the volunteer session.\n\nWe reserve the right to cancel volunteer 
 sessions up to two hours in advance. Possible reasons for cancelation are a
  change in COVID-19 guidelines as outlined by the University or County Offi
 cials\, excessive heat (90 degree and above)\, poor air quality\, rain or o
 ther inclement weather.\n\nWe encourage all volunteers to carpool\, bike\, 
 ride public transportation\; there is a charge for parking on all Stanford 
 property. The farm is not responsible for any tickets incurred while volunt
 eering.\n\nUPON ARRIVAL: ALL VOLUNTEERS MUST COMPLETE A SAFETY WAIVER \n\nW
 HEN YOU ARRIVE AT THE FARM: Complete Waiver Form
DTEND:20260523T183000Z
DTSTAMP:20260308T083914Z
DTSTART:20260523T163000Z
GEO:37.426059;-122.183261
LOCATION:O'Donohue Educational Farm
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Volunteering at Stanford Educational Farm
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51288078582720
URL:https://events.stanford.edu/event/copy-of-volunteering-at-the-stanford-
 educational-farm
END:VEVENT
